If insurers see behaviour which they think is inconsistent with statements provided about your claim, they will use this against you. This might cause:Significant reduction in the award of compensation that you may be offered or receive;The complete loss of your entitlements and rights altogether; andProsecution for fraud. Insurance companies have even posed as ''friends'' to gain access to clients  Facebook pages to determine if there is any information that can be used against them during the course of their claim, at times of negotiation or at trial.  Further, in the event that your matter proceeds to trial in the future, the Court has the power to order that you accept a social media  friend request  from a legal representative or insurer, in order to allow them access to your profile. Journalists also trawl social media sites in order to find photos and comments.  The risk to your claim arising from your use of social media cannot be overstated. It is easy for comments, photographs, videos, location  check-ins , activity tracking device records, etc. to give an impression that may be inconsistent with statements you have made about your claim, even when there is not any actual inconsistency. For example, a photograph of a person standing next to a group of people dancing may give the impression that the person was dancing, even if they were not; or a comment posted following a rehabilitative gym session may give the impression of physical activity beyond what actually occurred. It may be difficult months after the social media post to convince an insurer or a Court of the reality of the event the post describes or illustrates.We have recently acted in cases where social media postings by our clients have dramatically reduced the amount of compensation they were able to recover and have even prevented them from accessing compensation at all. You should therefore think very carefully about how your participation in social media might be perceived. If you are in any doubt whatsoever, do not post!If you do use social media, please ensure that you regularly check and, if necessary, update your privacy settings.  Please see the enclosed leaflet for advice on where to go to find your privacy settings.Whilst we encourage you to live your life as normally as possible, especially given the difficult times that you may be experiencing, we ask that you please consider advice contained in this letter and the implications of using the internet.  Please be very careful when using the internet, and in particular, social networking sites. Important points to remember during your claim:Be careful of ensuring the accurate recording of the nature of the accident/incident and your rehabilitation;Make sure that the information that you give to treating practitioners and to us is consistent and true;During the course of your claim, it is possible that you will be followed by private investigators on behalf of the insurance company and you will be subject to video surveillance;Be careful of the content of information that you share on the internet via social media;Be careful not to overstate or understate the impact of your injuries.  By being truthful about the impact of your injuries it will assist your treating practitioners to evaluate your injuries and determine appropriate rehabilitation treatment.  It will also enable us to ensure that you are appropriately compensated for your injuries;Keep a detailed diary;Keep all receipts for expenses incurred during the course of your claim and treatment;Most personal injury claims have both a physical and emotional impact.  It is important to discuss both matters with your treating practitioners and us;Any significant changes to your injuries or employment situation need to be discussed with us immediately. We recommend that you discuss any job offer with us prior to acceptance; andIf you think there is anything that we need to know, positive or negative, about your case please notify us immediately.If you have any queries regarding this letter, please contact us  PAGE      DOCVARIABLE "~FILE.PRINCIPLEFEEEARNER.INITIALS"    DOCVARIABLE "FILENO"    DOCVARIABLE "#USERINITS"   FILENAME  \* Upper  \* MERGEFORMAT   DOCVARIABLE "~FILE.PRINCIPLEFEEEARNER.INITIALS"    DOCVARIABLE "FILENO"    DOCVARIABLE "#USERINITS"   FILENAME   IF   DOCVARIABLE "PrecedentTitle" \* MERGEFORMAT   = "PRECEDENTTITLE : Not Found" "NF" "  DOCVARIABLE "PrecedentTitle"   IF   DOCVARIABLE "~FILE.BRANCH.ADDRESS.LINE5" \* MERGEFORMAT   = "SA" " h!JH h!JH h!JH h!JH h!JH h!JH h!JH h!JH h!JH h!JH h!JH h!JH h!JH gd!JH gd!JH gd!JH gd!JH gd!JH h8Y h8Y hvQ h8Y h8Y h!JH hvQ h!JH h!JH h!JH h!JH gd!JH gd8Y gd8Y gd8Y gd8Y gd!JH rnnnj`ZZ`T hS$ h8Y hS$ h8Y h8Y hS$ gd!JH hS$ hS$ hS$ hS$ mH	 sH	 hS$ hS$ hvQ hS$ hS$ ,Photoshop 3.0 8BIM X#http://ns.adobe.com/xap/1.0/ <?xpacket begin=" " id="W5M0MpCehiHzreSzNTczkc9d"?>
